- **Emit only what a clause names.** If the text gives no value for an optional parameter, omit it. If no clause calls for a second action, don't add one тАФ never invent a peer or modifier (no stray `variable.get`, `file.read`, `cache.wrap`) the text didn't ask for.
- **Never return an empty `actions` list for a step that has a clause.** Every real step maps to at least one action: `set %x% = %y%` тЖТ one `variable.set`; `call X` тЖТ one `goal.call`. If the planner's set genuinely lacks a needed action, emit the `missing-actions` error тАФ never return nothing.

Most steps are one action per clause. "This looks too simple" is almost always right.

## Write `formal` first

A one-line render of the chain; `actions[]` then mirrors it exactly.

`module.action(ParamName=value, ...)` тАФ real schema param names. Quote strings; keep `%vars%` verbatim; numbers/bools unquoted; lists `[...]`; objects `{k:v}`.
- Modifier follows its host with ` | ` : `host(...) | error.handle(Actions=[recovery(...)])`
- Peer follows with ` , ` : `condition.if(...) , goal.call(...)`
- Nested action values use `[...]` with the same syntax.

`formal` and `actions[]` MUST match exactly тАФ every `Param=value` in one appears in the other, no extras either way.

## Modifiers vs peers

Only THREE actions are modifiers тАФ `error.handle`, `cache.wrap`, `timeout.after` тАФ and they go in the host action's `modifiers[]`. Use one only when the step has a clause like `on error тАж`, `cache for тАж`, `timeout after тАж`. A `cache=` *parameter* on `llm.query` is NOT cache.wrap.

Everything else (`goal.call`, `variable.set`, `condition.if`, `loop.foreach`, `output.write`, `file.*`, `error.throw`, тАж) is a **peer** in the top-level `actions[]`, never in `modifiers[]`. `if X, call Y` and `foreach X, call Y` are two peers.

## `write to %x%` and `%!data%`

`тАж, write to %x%` тЖТ a trailing peer `variable.set(Name=%x%, Value=%!data%)` after the producer (never a modifier). `%!data%` is the immediately preceding action's return value тАФ use it ONLY to thread one action's result into the next when the text says so. It is not a fill-in for an unsupplied slot.

## Output shape

```json
{"formal":"...","actions":[...],"confidence":"VeryHigh|High|Medium|Low|VeryLow","explanation":"...","errors":[],"warnings":[]}
```

Each action: `{module, action, parameters:[{name, value, type}], modifiers?:[...]}`. `module` is a single identifier: `ui.render` тЖТ `{"module":"ui","action":"render"}`, never `{"module":"ui.render",...}`. Omit `explanation` at High/VeryHigh; otherwise one sentence on the uncertainty. Drop confidence to Low/VeryLow when the verb doesn't really match any action you were given.

## Parameters & types

- `name` is always the literal schema property name (`Name`, `Value`, `GoalName`, тАж). A `%var%` marker in a schema means "takes a variable reference" тАФ it is never a parameter name and says nothing about the runtime type. Don't raise warnings over type or letter-case differences.
- Type names come from the per-step Type reference (primitive names + kind table + catalog types) тАФ don't invent. `text` not `string`; `number` carries `int/long/decimal/double` as its *kind*; lists are `list<T>`. A JSON object/array value uses `type:"json"` as a structured value.
- Omit nullable params (`?`) when the text gives no value. NEVER emit `""` or copy a type descriptor (`actor?`, `eventtype`) into a value slot.

## Intermediates & compound conditions

- To branch on a producer's property, capture into a temp `__conditionReturn__` and reference `%__conditionReturn__.X%`.
- `if A and B, call C` тЖТ two `condition.if` peers + the `goal.call`; add `warnings:[{"key":"expanded-condition","message":"..."}]`.

## Errors

- `missing-actions` (top-level, exact key) тАФ the set lacks an action the step needs; emit and stop, don't fabricate a partial chain.
- Also: `actionNotFound`, `insufficientContext` (top-level); `ambiguousMapping`, `possibleTypo` (per action).

Never invent action names (`list.append`/`push`/`insert` don't exist тАФ use `list.add`). Preserve `%name%` literally everywhere, including `return`.

